detaileddescription.para: In older libdbus versions, this would be undefined if there was no 64-bit integer type on that platform. libdbus no longer supports such platforms.
The macro adds the necessary "LL" or whatever after the integer, giving a literal such as "325145246765LL"
The macro adds the necessary "ULL" or whatever after the integer, giving a literal such as "325145246765ULL"

briefdescription.para: The COMPILE TIME major version of libdbus, that is, the "X" in "X.Y.Z", as an integer literal.

detaileddescription.para: Consider carefully whether to use this or the runtime version from dbus_get_version().

briefdescription.para: The COMPILE TIME minor version of libdbus, that is, the "Y" in "X.Y.Z", as an integer literal.

detaileddescription.para: Consider carefully whether to use this or the runtime version from dbus_get_version().

briefdescription.para: The COMPILE TIME micro version of libdbus, that is, the "Z" in "X.Y.Z", as an integer literal.

detaileddescription.para: Consider carefully whether to use this or the runtime version from dbus_get_version().

briefdescription.para: The COMPILE TIME version of libdbus, as a string "X.Y.Z".

detaileddescription.para: Consider carefully whether to use this or the runtime version from dbus_get_version().

briefdescription.para: The COMPILE TIME version of libdbus, as a single integer that has 0 in the most significant byte, the major version in the next most significant byte, the minor version in the third most significant, and the micro version in the least significant byte.

detaileddescription.para: This means two DBUS_VERSION can be compared to see which is higher.
Consider carefully whether to use this or the runtime version from dbus_get_version().

briefdescription.para: A 32-bit signed integer on all platforms.
A 32-bit unsigned integer on all platforms.
A 16-bit signed integer on all platforms.
A 16-bit unsigned integer on all platforms.
